-- Japanese Stock Futures, Australian Shares Rise on China Currency Reserves
-- B y   N o r i e   K u b o y a m a
-- 2010-10-13T23:20:28Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-13/japanese-stock-futures-australian-shares-rise-on-china-currency-reserves.html
Japanese  stock   futures  and
Australian shares rose after China’s foreign-currency reserves
climbed by a record last month, boosting investors’ confidence
in a global economic recovery.  American depositary receipts of Canon Inc., a Japanese
camera maker that gets about 80 percent of its sales abroad,
gained 0.9 percent from the closing share price in Tokyo. Those
of Toyota Motor Corp., a carmaker that gets more than 70 percent
of its sales overseas, increased 1.1 percent. BHP Billiton Ltd.,
the world’s largest mining company and Australia’s biggest oil
producer, advanced 1.4 percent as oil and metal prices gained.  “China, which is a major source of demand, is unexpectedly
good,” said  Mitsushige Akino , who oversees about $450 million
in assets in Tokyo at Ichiyoshi Investment Management Co.
“Global economic sentiment is moderately recovering and
excessive pessimism is receding.”  Futures on Japan’s  Nikkei 225 Stock Average  expiring in
December closed at 9,500 in Chicago yesterday, compared with
9,420 in Singapore. They were bid in the pre-market at 9,510 in
Osaka, Japan, at 8:05 a.m. local time. Australia’s  S&P/ASX 200
Index  advanced 1.2 percent today. New Zealand’s  NZX 50 Index 
gained 0.7 percent in Wellington.  Futures on the  Standard & Poor’s 500 Index  were little
changed today. The index rose 0.7 percent yesterday in New York
to the highest close since May 3.  CSX Corp. , the second-largest
publicly traded U.S. railroad, reported profit that exceeded
analysts’ estimates, and China said its foreign-exchange
reserves increased by a record to $2.65 trillion at the end of
September.  Valuations, Commodities  The  MSCI Asia Pacific Index  rose 0.7 percent yesterday, the
biggest gain in a week, as reports from China, Japan and
Australia showed the economic recovery is strengthening. The
gauge has advanced 7.6 percent in 2010, compared with gains of
5.7 percent by the  S&P 500  and 4.9 percent by the  Stoxx Europe
600 Index . Stocks in the Asian benchmark are valued at an
average of 14.3 times estimated  earnings , compared with 14 times
for the S&P and 12.3 times for the Stoxx.  Crude oil for November delivery rose 1.6 percent to settle
at $83.01 a barrel yesterday in New York, the highest level
since Oct. 6. The  London Metal Exchange Index  of six metals
including aluminum and copper advanced 0.3 percent yesterday to
the highest close since July 2008. The  Baltic Dry Index  of
shipping rates for commodities rose for a second consecutive day.  To contact the reporter for this story:
 Norie Kuboyama  in Tokyo at 
 nkuboyama@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at   ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 